---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '../lib/site';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="serial-sync | Patreon-first sync utility"
  description="A workflow site for serial-sync, the dump-first Patreon sync utility."
  currentPath="/"
>
  <div class="page">
    <section class="hero">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Patreon-first. Dump-first. Docker-first.</p>
        <h1>Turn paid creator feeds into durable serial artifacts.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          serial-sync keeps the public CLI intentionally small: `setup`, `run`, and `debug`.
          Use `setup dump` to build an offline authoring workspace, refine series rules without
          re-hitting Patreon, then run production syncs through the intended container runtime.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button" href={withBase('/getting-started/')}>Get started</a>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={withBase('/rules/')}>Author rules</a>
        </div>
        <div class="meta-row">
          <span class="chip">CLI: `setup` `run` `debug`</span>
          <span class="chip">Output modes: `preserve` and `epub`</span>
          <span class="chip">Auth: saved Patreon session reuse</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proof-panel">
        <div class="proof-panel__label">First success loop</div>
        <pre><code>serial-sync setup auth --source example-creator
serial-sync setup dump --auth-profile patreon-default --path ./serial-sync-rule-workspace --force
serial-sync setup preview --workspace ./serial-sync-rule-workspace --series-file ./serial-sync-rule-workspace/series.toml --show-posts
serial-sync run --dry-run --source example-creator</code></pre>
        <p>
          The product is the loop: authenticate once, dump memberships, preview series locally,
          then run with confidence.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>What this repo is for</h2>
      <p>
        `serial-sync` is a Patreon-first sync utility. It fetches paid creator content, classifies
        releases into series, materializes canonical artifacts, and publishes them through simple
        downstream targets.
      </p>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <article class="card">
          <p class="card__label">1. Source</p>
          <h3>Authenticate and discover</h3>
          <p>Use Patreon credentials or a saved session to discover creators, collections, and memberships.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <p class="card__label">2. Author</p>
          <h3>Dump and refine rules offline</h3>
          <p>Write series rules against a local workspace until fallback only catches true miscellany.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <p class="card__label">3. Operate</p>
          <h3>Run, debug, and recover</h3>
          <p>Production syncs stay inspectable through logs, events, publish records, and support bundles.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Route map</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <article class="panel">
          <h3>Getting started</h3>
          <p>One Docker-first path from config to first dry-run.</p>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={withBase('/getting-started/')}>Open the guide</a>
        </article>
        <article class="panel">
          <h3>Authoring rules</h3>
          <p>How to use `setup dump` and `setup preview` to shape series definitions.</p>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={withBase('/rules/')}>Open the guide</a>
        </article>
        <article class="panel">
          <h3>Production</h3>
          <p>How the sync runs safely in a container, reuses sessions, and handles recovery.</p>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={withBase('/production/')}>Open the guide</a>
        </article>
        <article class="panel">
          <h3>Reference and troubleshooting</h3>
          <p>Use these pages when you need exact commands or recovery paths.</p>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={withBase('/reference/')}>Open the reference</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
